# hilavitkutin-kit Design Overview

`#![no_std]`, zero deps. Ships exactly one trait, `Kit`. The
hilavitkutin engine depends on this crate so its
`SchedulerBuilder<Wus, Stores>` can offer `.add_kit::<K>()`. The
reverse direction does not exist. A Kit is a declarative bundle:
it names the WorkUnits it ships and the stores it owns. The engine
reads those declarations at compile time and accumulates them into
the scheduler's typestate.

## Purpose

The scheduler builder accumulates type-state across each
registration call. Most consumer apps register the same handful of
WorkUnits and stores together: a runner WU plus its column outputs,
a logger WU plus its diagnostic store, an interner Resource. A Kit
captures one such bundle by declaring `type Units` (the WorkUnits)
and `type Owned` (the stores).

Authoring a Kit is purely a type-level statement. Kit authors do
not write an `install` method, do not compose builder method
chains, do not name `SchedulerBuilder` anywhere. The engine's
`.add_kit::<K>()` reads `K::Units` and `K::Owned` at compile time
and prepends them onto the SchedulerBuilder's accumulators via
`Concat`.

The crate exists separately so the Kit shape lives below the
engine but above the api / ctx layer. A consumer can author Kits
without pulling the engine in. Future Kit-related helpers (if any
recurring patterns surface) ship here.

## The trait

```rust
pub trait Kit {
    type Units: WorkUnitBundle;
    type Owned: StoreBundle;
}
```

Two associated types only. `Units` is a cons-list of `WorkUnit`
declarations the Kit ships; `Owned` is a cons-list of store markers
(`Resource<T>` / `Column<T>` / `Virtual<T>`) the Kit declares as
its own. Both bounds (`WorkUnitBundle`, `StoreBundle`) are
core primitives in `hilavitkutin-api`.

The trait carries no `Required` member and no `requirements_doc()`
helper. Topic 3 originally proposed `Required` as an associated
type derivable from `Units::AccessSet \ Owned`; the audit M6
investigation (`mock/research/sketches/202605050800_dedup_concat/`)
confirmed that the type-level set difference operator hits the
same coherence wall as round-3's NotIn proof. Round-4 drops the
claim. "What a kit requires" lives in prose: the kit author
documents required external Resources (Resources the kit reads but
does not own) in the Kit's rustdoc.

## Authoring a Kit

A consumer-side Kit that owns a `RunnerKit` shape with one WU plus
two output columns:

```rust
pub struct RunnerKit;

impl Kit for RunnerKit {
    type Units = read![RunnerWu];
    type Owned = read![Column<RunnerOutput>, Column<RunnerStats>];
}
```

The `read!` macro from `hilavitkutin-api` expands the flat list
into the `Cons<H, T>` cons-list shape `WorkUnitBundle` and
`StoreBundle` recursive impls consume.

A Kit that bundles WUs but no Owned state (for example a "tracing
fiber" preset that reads several columns and writes to a Resource
the app provides):

```rust
pub struct TracingKit;

impl Kit for TracingKit {
    type Units = read![TracerFiber, SampleCollector];
    type Owned = read![];
}
```

Empty `Owned` is fine; the empty cons-list satisfies `StoreBundle`
trivially. The Kit's WUs read from external Resources (Tracer,
Diagnostic, etc.) which the app registers separately or via other
Kits' `Owned` declarations.

A Kit that ships only Owned state with no WUs of its own (a pure
provider-preset, like `InternerKit` from `hilavitkutin-providers`):

```rust
pub struct InternerKit<const BYTES: usize, const ENTRIES: usize>;

impl<const BYTES: usize, const ENTRIES: usize> Kit
    for InternerKit<BYTES, ENTRIES>
{
    type Units = read![];
    type Owned = read![Resource<StringInterner<MemoryArena<BYTES, ENTRIES>>>];
}
```

The kit declares the type-level commitment that the StringInterner
Resource exists in `Stores`. The actual value is supplied at the
app's call site via `builder.resource(default_interner::<...>())`,
since the api has no `Kit::default_resources()` association
(see BACKLOG entry).

### Kit-internal types and visibility

Kit authors face one structural constraint surfaced by the round-4
S5 sketch: every type appearing in a `pub Kit` impl's `type Owned`
position must be at least as visible as the impl itself. Rust's
E0446 ("private type in public interface") forbids `pub(crate)`
or module-private types in pub-trait associated-type positions.
The two workable kit-shape patterns:

1. **Whole-kit pub**: the Kit struct, every Owned type, every
   WorkUnit type are all `pub`. "Kit-internal" is a documentation
   convention applied by the kit author (typically by keeping
   non-Replaceable types out of the kit's public re-export
   surface). The kit framework cannot enforce kit-internalness;
   convention is the only signal.
2. **Whole-kit pub(crate) within a per-kit crate**: the kit ships
   in its own crate; Kit struct and Owned types are all
   `pub(crate)`. Consumers outside the kit's crate cannot name the
   kit directly; the kit's crate provides a `pub` helper-fn that
   consumes a builder and returns one without naming the kit. This
   is the genuine kit-private mode.

A single Kit impl cannot mix levels. Round-4 kits ship using
pattern (1); switching to pattern (2) is an optional kit-author
choice when kit-private state is genuinely required at the crate
boundary.

See `mock/research/sketches/202605050615_kit_taxonomy/FINDINGS.md`
for the empirical evidence behind this constraint and
`mock/design_rounds/202605042200_topic_round_4_layered_enforcement.md`
for the corresponding framing.

### Kits in crates that cannot import the engine

The Kit declaration is purely a type-level statement; it depends
only on `hilavitkutin-api` (for `WorkUnitBundle`, `StoreBundle`,
`Replaceable`, plus the `Resource<T>` / `Column<T>` / `Virtual<T>`
markers) and on `hilavitkutin-kit` itself (for the `Kit` trait).
Kit-author crates do not import `hilavitkutin::*` directly; the
forbidden-imports rule continues to apply and is trivially
satisfied by the new shape.

The v0.1 BuilderResource bridge layer (which let a Kit's `install`
method call `builder.with_resource(...)` against any builder type)
is gone. The new shape has no `install` method and never names a
builder; the bridge is unnecessary.

## Composition

Kits compose by being added in sequence on the SchedulerBuilder:

```rust
let scheduler = Scheduler::builder()
    .resource::<StringInterner<...>>(default_interner())
    .add_kit::<RunnerKit>()
    .add_kit::<LinterKit>()
    .add_kit::<TracingKit>()
    .build();
```

Each `.add_kit::<K>()` accumulates `K::Units` into the bundle and
`K::Owned` into the stores via type-level `Concat`. Order matters
for the `ContainsAll<Wus::AccumRead>` proof at `.build()`: a Kit
whose WUs read from another Kit's Owned state is fine, but the
Owned state must be in the accumulated `Stores` by the time
`.build()` resolves the bound. Adding kits in dependency order is
the simplest discipline; the builder accepts any order that
satisfies the proof.

A Kit cannot install another Kit inside its declaration; there is
no install body to write. Kit composition is the consumer's
choice via the builder chain. If a kit author wants to bundle
multiple kits behind a single registration, they declare a
"super-kit" whose `Units` and `Owned` are the union of the inner
kits' projections (achievable via `Concat` composition at the type
level, written out in the super-kit's impl).

## Replaceable: enforced override gating

`Replaceable` is the only enforced annotation on Owned types.
The marker lives in `hilavitkutin-api`; kit authors opt in
per type:

```rust
pub struct LintConfig;
impl Replaceable for LintConfig {}  // app may override via .replace_resource

pub struct RoundState;
// no impl Replaceable: locked, cannot be overridden
```

The static `T: Replaceable` bound on
`Scheduler::replace_resource::<T>(value)` (declared in the engine
crate) rejects override attempts on non-opt-in types at compile
time. See `hilavitkutin-api::Replaceable` and
`hilavitkutin::Scheduler::replace_resource` for the trait
documentation; see S4 (`mock/research/sketches/202605050555_replaceable_polarity/`)
for the polarity decision (opt-in is safer-by-default per the
"tools, not policies" workspace rule).

## Why a separate crate

`hilavitkutin-kit` slots between `hilavitkutin-ctx` and the
engine. The crate carries no other dependencies; the engine
depends on it for `.add_kit::<K>()`, but the reverse never
happens. A consumer can author a Kit in a downstream crate that
depends only on `hilavitkutin-kit` plus the bare api markers
(`Resource<T>`, `Column<T>`, `Virtual<T>`, `WorkUnitBundle`,
`StoreBundle`, `Replaceable` from `hilavitkutin-api`) without
pulling the engine in.

The layering is the same shape `hilavitkutin-ctx` has: an
ecosystem crate the engine consumes for one specific contract.

## Crate-internal recursion limit

This crate declares `#![recursion_limit = "512"]` defensively. A
consumer composing deep Kit chains sends the trait solver through
the cons-list at each `.add_kit` call (Concat recursion) and again
at `.build()` (ContainsAll recursion plus WorkUnitBundle accumulator
recursion). The default 128 suffices for shallow chains; 512
covers realistic compositions without consumer-side awareness. If
a consumer's own crate hits the limit anyway, the consumer
declares its own `#![recursion_limit = "..."]` at the consumer
crate root.

S1b's depth-5 sketch (`mock/research/sketches/202605050700_deep_stacking_d5/`)
confirms 25 WUs at 5 tiers compile in 0.53s without exceeding the
512 limit.

## Deferred ergonomics

A declarative `app!` / `define_app!` macro that folds
`.add::<WU>()` / `.resource()` / `.column()` / `.add_kit()` calls
into a single block was considered and parked at task #295 (P2,
likely never). Bevy proves the raw builder pattern is
ergonomically sufficient at the call counts viola, vehje, and
similar consumers reach (around ten registrations per app). The
macro adds complexity without a measurable readability win at
that scale.

If a downstream consumer surfaces a real ergonomics complaint,
revisit #295.
